<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n50089a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n50" href="#n50089a">N50 (VI.B.37)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n50all.htm#n50089a"> 89(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> clapbread / board cloth / bink (on the)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">These originally Scandinavian words are now chiefly found in the north-west of England, among the remote mountains of Yorkshire, Westmoreland, Cumberland, and Lancashire, where they have withstood the changes of time. On entering a house there one will find the housewife <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> whilst standing by her <i>back-bword</i> (<i>Dan</i>., Bagebord; <i>Eng</i>., baking-board) she is about to knead <i>dough</i> (<i>Dan</i>., Deig), in order to make the oaten bread commonly used in these parts, at times, also, barley-bread; for <mark>clap-bread</mark> (Dan. Klappebr&ouml;d, or thin cakes beaten out with the hand) she lays the dough on the <i>clap-board</i> (<i>Dan</i>., Klappebord). One will also find the <mark><i>bord-claith</i></mark> spread (<i>Dan</i>., Bordkl&aelig;de; <i>Eng</i>., table-cloth); the people of the house then sit <mark>on the <i>bank</i> or <i>bink</i></mark> (<i>Dan</i>., B&aelig;nk; <i>Eng</i>., bench), and eat Aandorn (<i>Eng</i>., afternoon&apos;s repast), or, as it is called in Jutland and F&uuml;nen, Onden (dinner). <small> J.J.A. Worsaae, <a name="JJAW2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#JJAW2"><cite title="source">An Account of the Danes and Norwegians in England, Scotland and Ireland</cite></a> (1852) 82</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
